text: These three core data points are enough to satiate my requirements as an investor. And they should be something you pay attention on.
I don't care if you're from IIT or IIM or a small-town college dropout
column4: all it matters to me is your product

text: You don't define the entire startup ecosystem. You're one team.
Similarly
column4: if your idea is amazing
column5: or if it's a bunch of guys who think everyone should fall at their feet and just throw money on them...

text: But either ways
column4: I don't define the entire investment subculture. I am just one person or one AIF. I am not everybody.

text: If I am an arrogant asshole
column4: I'll ask you to fuck right off.

text: I am investor and I will protect my interests. If I am a nice guy
column4: I'll tell you what is wrong with your idea.

text: If you have a strong team put together
column4: the collective efforts matter. The product then becomes obsolete

text: If it is not working
column4: don't necessarily wind up. Try pivoting. Snapdeal was a groupon's clone
column5: it is now an amazon/flipkart clone.

text: You need to know that no one can put you down. Not an investor
column4: not your peers
column5: not your competition. But be rational about your business.

text: And comparisons se koi startup nahi banta. So a "Facebook for Photographers" is worthless
column4: but a "Photography Social Network" may be worthy.

text: You need data
column4: prospects
column6: competition analysis and everything else in there. Emotions pe koi paise nahi lagata.

text: So have patience
column4: keep working on your idea and keep soliciting investors. A product alone will rarely get you money.
